SMART CLASSROOM FOR ENHANCED LEARNING 

 

SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW 

The Virtual AI Mouse Cursor system is built using a modular architecture comprising the following key components: 

 

1. Input Subsystem: Real-Time Video Capture 

  • Hardware: The system relies on a webcam as its primary input device to capture real-time video. 

  • Software: The OpenCV library is used to access the webcam feed (cv2.VideoCapture(0)). Each frame is captured as an image for further processing. 

  • Key Steps: 

  • 1.Frames are flipped horizontally (cv2.flip()) to ensure a mirrored view for intuitive control. 

  • 2.Captured frames are converted from BGR to RGB format (cv2.cvtColor()), preparing them for further processing with MediaPipe. 

    •  

    2. Hand Gesture Detection Subsystem 

  • Purpose: Detects and identifies hand gestures by locating key landmarks on the user's hand. 

  • Core Technology: The MediaPipe Hands module. 

  • Key Functions: 

  • oHand Detection: The Hand() object processes the RGB frames and identifies multiple hand landmarks in real-time. 

  • oLandmark Drawing: Detected landmarks are drawn on the frames using mp.solutions.drawing_utils, aiding visualization for debugging and testing. 

  • oData Extraction: The coordinates (x, y) of specific landmarks (e.g., index finger tip and thumb tip) are extracted for gesture recognition. 

    •  

    3. Gesture Recognition Subsystem 

  • Purpose: Interprets specific hand gestures and maps them to corresponding mouse actions. 

  • Key Gestures: 

  • 1.Cursor Movement: 

  • Index finger tip (id == 8) is tracked. 

  • Coordinates are mapped from the video frame's dimensions to the screen resolution using scaling factors (screen_width / frame_width and screen_height / frame_height). 

  • Cursor is moved to the corresponding screen position using pyautogui.moveTo(). 

  • 2.Click Action: 

  • Thumb tip (id == 4) and index finger tip proximity are measured (abs(index_y - thumb_y)). 

    • 17  

      

    17

  • A click is triggered if the distance between these landmarks equals zero (pyautogui.click()). 

  • A brief delay (pyautogui.sleep(0)) is added to prevent multiple clicks from being registered rapidly. 

    •  

    4. Screen Mapping Subsystem 

  • Purpose: Ensures smooth and accurate mapping of the camera feed's resolution to the screen's resolution. 

  • Implementation: 

  • oThe screen dimensions are retrieved using the pyautogui.size() function. 

  • oCoordinates from the camera feed are scaled proportionally to match the virtual screen. 

  • oThis scaling ensures that hand gestures correspond accurately to physical locations on the screen. 

    •  

    5. Output Subsystem: Cursor Control 

  • Purpose: Executes the recognized gestures as mouse actions on the system. 

  • Implementation: 

  • oThe cursor's position is updated in real-time using pyautogui.moveTo(). 

  • oMouse clicks are performed based on the proximity of the thumb and index finger. 

  • oVisual feedback is provided via the drawn landmarks (cv2.circle()), showing gesture activity in the video feed. 

    •  

    6. User Interface Subsystem 

  • Purpose: Displays the processed video feed to the user, providing real-time feedback. 

  • Implementation: 

  • oThe processed frames are displayed in a separate window (cv2.imshow('Virtual Mouse', frame)). 

  • oUsers can exit the application by pressing the Q key (cv2.waitKey(1)). 

    •  

    7. System Flow 

  • 1.Initialization: The camera feed and required modules (OpenCV, MediaPipe, PyAutoGUI) are initialized. 

  • 2.Video Processing Loop: Frames are captured and processed in a continuous loop. 

  • 3.Gesture Detection: MediaPipe identifies hand landmarks and gestures. 

  • 4.Action Mapping: Detected gestures are mapped to cursor movements and mouse actions. 

  • 5.Feedback Loop: The system updates the cursor position and provides visual feedback to the user in real-time. 

  • 6.Termination: The loop terminates when the user presses the Q key, releasing the camera and closing all windows. 

    •  

    18  

      

    18

    This architecture ensures that the system is modular, efficient, and scalable. Each subsystem focuses on a specific task, and together they provide a seamless user experience for controlling the cursor using hand gestures. 

    4.1 Design and Workflow: 

    The design of the Virtual AI Mouse Cursor system focuses on transforming hand gestures into cursor movements and mouse actions through a series of structured processes. 

    Workflow: 

  • 1.Real-Time Input Capture: 

  • oA webcam captures video frames continuously. 

  • oEach frame represents a snapshot of the hand gestures in real-time. 

  • 2.Frame Preprocessing: 

  • oFrames are flipped horizontally for a mirrored view, ensuring intuitive control. 

  • oColors are converted from BGR to RGB to match MediaPipe's input requirements. 

  • 3.Hand Gesture Detection: 

  • oMediaPipe detects the user's hand and identifies key landmarks. 

  • oLandmark coordinates are normalized relative to the frame dimensions. 

  • 4.Gesture Interpretation: 

  • oSpecific hand landmarks (index finger tip, thumb tip) are monitored. 

  • oGestures such as finger movement and proximity are interpreted as cursor movements and click actions. 

  • 5.Cursor Control and Action Execution: 

  • oThe detected gestures are mapped to the screen's dimensions. 

  • oPyAutoGUI moves the cursor and performs click actions based on recognized gestures. 

  • 6.Feedback Display: 

  • oVisual feedback, such as drawn landmarks and action indicators, is provided in the displayed video frame. 

  • oThis ensures users can see the system's interpretation of their gestures. 

    •  

    4.2 Implementation: 

    4.2.1 Camera Input Setup with OpenCV 

  • Objective: Initialize the webcam and capture real-time video frames. 

  • Steps: 

  • 1.OpenCV's cv2.VideoCapture(0) is used to access the webcam. 

  • 2.The camera feed is processed in a continuous loop. 

  • 3.Frames are flipped horizontally for a mirror effect and resized as needed. 

  • Code Snippet: 

    • [python] 

    cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0) 

    _, frame = cap.read() 

    frame = cv2.flip(frame, 1)  # Flip for mirror effect
